value.value: An ice floe which is formed from frozen sea water, and floats upon the surface of a marine water body.
A sea ice floe which has a rounded or circular shape and raised rims.
A sea ice floe which is thin, elastic, continuous, and of a transparent gray color, which results from the freezing of new ice.
A sea ice floe which is inflexible and thicker than nilas.
Sea ice which has formed over a single freezing season.

Sea ice develops from young ice; thickness from 0.3 to 2 meters (1 to 6.6 feet).  Sea ice be subdivided into thin first-year ice (white ice), medium first-year ice, and thick first-year ice.  First-year ice is distinguished from older ice primarily by having a higher salinity. Undeformed first-year ice differs from older ice in that it is smoother and lacks refrozen melt ponds. Characteristically level where undisturbed by pressure, but where ridges occur, they  distinguished by being larger, more angular, and more porous than multiyear ridges.
Sea ice which is thicker than first year ice, and has survived a seasonal melting process.
Sea ice which is thicker than second year ice, and has survived more than two seasonal melting process.
A layer which consists of a thin aggregate of frazil ice crystals, which float upon the surface of a water body.

definition.value: Within a marine system, grease ice makes the ocean surface resemble an oil slick.

value.value: New ice, which is spongy, lumpy and opaque, and forms from water which freezes in an agitated water body.

definition.value: These new ice classes refer to both marine water and fresh water ice. If using this term for annotation, use it in conjunction with another envo term to express whether the ice is in a marine, freshwater, or other system.

value.value: A slurry of frazil, snow, and liquid water.

definition.value: These new ice classes refer to both marine water and fresh water ice. If using this term for annotation, use it in conjunction with another envo term to express whether the ice is in a marine, freshwater, or other system.

value.value: A layer which consists of slush ice.

definition.value: A new ice formation process in which slush ice is formed.
A new ice formation process in which shuga is formed.

value.value: A freshwater lake which fills a depression formed by the erosion of thermokarst caused by permafrost thaw.

definition.value: Continued thawing of the permafrost substrate can lead to the drainage and eventual disappearance of thermokarst lakes, leaving only the landform, thermokarst depression behind.

value.value: A thermokarst lake through which methane gas released from thawing permafrost, or other methane stores, rises and escapes to the atmosphere.

definition.value: On Earth, the bright blue appearance, in the light spectrum visible to humans, is due to increased abundances of microorganisms attracted to sulfur compounds associated with the methane release.

value.value: A geographic basin which is formed due to the erosion of thermokarst by meltwater released from thawing permafrost.
An irregular land surface which consists of marshy hollows, hummocks, thermokarst depressions and thermokarst lakes formed from the erosion of ice-rich thawing permafrost areas.

definition.value: Thermokarst is usually found in Arctic or mountainous areas.

value.value: A permafrost thawing process during which water-based ice or snow present in permafrost is converted into meltwater.
Permafrost which contains pockets of trapped methane gas.

definition.value: Other hydrocarbon gasses such as carbon dioxide may also be present. These pockets can be sufficently large that the permafrost surface will undulate when pressure is applied.

label.value: permafrost crater derived from a methane explosion

value.value: A crater which is found in permafrost and formed as a result of an explosion fuelled by methane formerly contained in that permafrost.
A process during which a material entity undergoes a rapid increase in volume, releasing gasses and various forms of energy, often including thermal, light and sound energy.

definition.value: Supersonic explosions are known as detonations and subsonic explosions as deflagrations.

value.value: An explosion during which methane-rich gas trapped in permafrost combusts.
A material transport process during which a portion of gaseous environmental material is transported into the atmosphere.
A gas emission process during which a portion of hydrocarbon gas is transported into the atmosphere.

definition.value: Some hydrocarbon gasses within the atmosphere contribute to the planetary green house gas effect by increasing absorption of solar energy.

value.value: A hydrocarbon gas emission process during which a portion of methane gas is transported into the atmosphere.

definition.value: Methane is emitted during the production and transport of coal, natural gas, and oil. Methane emissions also result from livestock and other agricultural practices and by the decay of organic waste in municipal solid waste landfills.

A process during which the intesity of stellar radiation received by a planet's surface varies in a cyclical regime due to the planet's orbital motion around the barycentre of a planetary system and/or the tilt of its rotational axis relative to its orbital plane.

The seasons that are generated by this process are divisions of time between warm (maximal radiation exposure) and cold (minimum radiation exposure) extremes. Depending on the planet's makeup, the resulting seasonal dynamics may include ecological and meteorological cycles which may form the basis for further divisions of the cycle (e.g. rainy season, dry season, wildfire season).
A one-dimensional temporal region which is delimited by the occurrence of processes which serve as its delimiters.
A season during which the average temperature of a planetary part exceeds that of all other seasons it endures during a season generating process.

The boundaries of seasons are typically fiat and should be defined on a data/information layer. This also pertains to the amount of time included when averaging measured values of qualities like temperature.
A season during which the average temperature of a planetary part is below that of all other seasons it endures during a season generating process.

The boundaries of seasons are typically fiat and should be defined on a data/information layer. This also pertains to the amount of time included when averaging measured values of qualities like temperature.
A material transformation process during which a material entity melts during a warm season.

value.value: A compaction process during which a material entity subjected to heat and/or pressure is compacted into a solid mass without undergoing melting.
A sintering process during which snow is compacted into glacial ice.
An aeolian transport process during which powdery snow is displaced and moved.

definition.value: An accumulation process during which a powdery snow carried on the wind settles on a solid surface, forming a mound.

value.value: A mass wasting process during which slab snow rapidly moves down a sloping surface.

definition.value: Slab avalanches account for most back-country fatalities.

value.value: An avalanche during which powdery snow rapidly flows down a sloping surface.
An avalanche during which a suspension of water and snow flows down a sloping surface.

definition.value: Wet snow avalanches travel at a lower velocity than other types of avalanches.

value.value: Snow which is cohesive, hard and overlies weaker snow.

definition.value: A solid astronomical body part which is primarily composed of a continuous mass of snow and/or ice.
A mass of snow.

value.value: An accumulation of powdery snow which was transported and deposited via a snow drifting process.

definition.value: An accumulation of snow and firn which rests upon land.
A snow patch which forms during a cold season and melts away during the succeeding warm season.
A snow patch which persists through at least one seasonal cycle.
A snow patch is defined as perennial if it survives two or more melt seasons.

value.value: A snow mass which is large enough, and persists long enough, to undergo compaction under its own weight, leading to layer-like structural differentiation.

definition.value: Snowpack is found in geographic regions experiencing cold weather for extended periods of time.

The GCW analysis of multiple glossaries found eight definitions of snowpack, with many commonalities but also disagreements. Please see the corresponding report "WMO GCW Nomenclature Assessment" for more information.

value.value: A structure which traverses a mass of one or more environmental materials, and encloses a roughly tubular site.

label.value: atmosphere and water column exposed melt pond

definition.value: A melt pond which and is exposed to the atmosphere and to a lesser degree water underlying the ice mass which contains it.
A melt pond which is formed close to that part of an ice mass which is in contact with some underlying water body, and which has channels connecting it to that water body.

value.value: A lake which is situated beneath a glacier.
An erosion process during which rock or soil is removed or degraded due to alternative thawing and freezing of meltwater beneath and at the margins of snowbanks.
